<paragraph blockId="10.[264,1323,631,1906]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,385,1510,1536]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Head.</emphasis>
Completely covered with minute pale hairs, generally black, but the eye stalks are brown. Facial teeth 
<number box="[557,594,1551,1577]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="1.5">1.5</number>
times longer than width of eye stalks in the middle. Outer vertical bristles at least as long as width of the eye stalk in the middle. Inner vertical bristles minute and weak, shorter than 
<number box="[717,728,1634,1660]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[740,755,1634,1660]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="3.0">3</number>
rd of width of the eye stalk in the middle.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[264,1323,631,1906]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,412,1673,1699]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Thorax.</emphasis>
Uniformly grayish pollinose, except the surface of the meron. Metapleural spine yellow or orange yellow and straight in anterior view. Scutellar spines 
<number box="[1156,1221,1714,1740]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="2.75" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.5">2.5–3</number>
times as long as the scutellum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[264,1323,631,1906]" lastBlockId="11.[264,1323,284,1156]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,484,1793,1819]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Wing 
<figureCitation box="[389,478,1793,1819]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 &amp; 10" captionStartId="7.[264,382,1812,1836]" captionTargetBox="[296,1291,1052,1784]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[296,1291,1052,1785]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 9 &amp; 10: D. comoroensis (9) and D. meigenii (10) wings. The larger apical band is clearly visible in the D. meigenii wing, spanning between the M and R 2 + 3 veins." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/172486/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Fig. 
<number box="[447,478,1793,1819]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
.
</emphasis>
Completely hyaline, except for three infuscated brownish bands. The apical band is as broad as 
<number box="[566,576,1836,1862]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[587,618,1836,1862]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="14.0">14</number>
th of the wing length and is restricted to the space between M and R 
<number box="[334,344,1889,1906]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number box="[355,364,1889,1906]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="3.0">3</number>
veins (the band reaches these veins). The central band is darkest around R 
<number box="[1243,1253,1889,1906]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="4.0">4</number>
+ 
<number box="[1264,1273,1889,1906]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="5.0">5</number>
and it is situated between R 
<number box="[536,546,296,313]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number box="[558,567,296,313]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="3.0">3</number>
and Cu slightly extended towards the anterior cross vein (R–M). The proximal band is more an infuscated brownish spot below the cell cup.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[264,1323,284,1156]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,475,366,392]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Legs 
<figureCitation box="[380,469,366,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 &amp; 12" captionStartId="7.[264,382,1881,1905]" captionText="FIGURES 11 &amp; 12: D. comoroensis (11) and D. meigenii (12) first coxae." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Fig. 
<number box="[438,469,366,392]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
.
</emphasis>
Front coxae are only shiny on the posterior surface. Legs are yellowbrown in general, tibiae and first two tarsi of the front leg are black, tarsi 
<number box="[1131,1177,407,433]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5</number>
on the front leg are whitish yellow (clearly contrasting the other tarsi). Front femora incrassate (length/ width approximately 
<number box="[530,547,487,513]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="4.0">4</number>
), bearing on their ventral side two longitudinal rows of 
<number box="[1280,1323,487,513]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
prominent bristles each and between these two rows of 
<number box="[968,1040,527,553]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="26.0" valueMax="28.0" valueMin="24.0">24–28</number>
much shorter peg­like tubercles each.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[264,1323,284,1156]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,478,606,632]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Preabdomen.</emphasis>
Subshining black except for the following silver pollinose areas: an uninterrupted band along posterior margin of tergite 
<number box="[881,896,647,673]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="1.0">1</number>
, lateral triangles at posterior margin of tergite 
<number box="[377,394,687,713]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="2.0">2</number>
, distal half of tergite 
<number box="[644,660,687,713]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="3.0">3</number>
, and subsequent tergites.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[264,1323,284,1156]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,735,726,752]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Postabdomen (male) 
<figureCitation box="[590,730,726,752]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 20" captionStartId="9.[264,383,1778,1802]" captionTargetBox="[397,1195,325,1770]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[389,1200,317,1787]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 20: D. meigenii male genitalia. 9: ventral view, 10: detailed ventral view with surstyli, gonopods, cerci (no hairs on cerci drawn), 11: detailed lateral view with gonopod and paramere, 12: lateral view with aedeagal apodeme, hypandrium and epandrium. Scale bar 0.4 mm for Fig 17, 20, 0.2 mm for Fig 18 and 0.1 mm for Fig 19." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/172488/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Figs 
<number box="[657,730,726,752]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="18.5" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="17.0">17–20</number>
</figureCitation>
.
</emphasis>
The hypandrium is connected to the aedeagal apodeme and the membranous tip of the hypandrium is continuous, not divided into two lobes anteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[478,572,807,833]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 20" captionStartId="9.[264,383,1778,1802]" captionTargetBox="[397,1195,325,1770]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[389,1200,317,1787]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 20: D. meigenii male genitalia. 9: ventral view, 10: detailed ventral view with surstyli, gonopods, cerci (no hairs on cerci drawn), 11: detailed lateral view with gonopod and paramere, 12: lateral view with aedeagal apodeme, hypandrium and epandrium. Scale bar 0.4 mm for Fig 17, 20, 0.2 mm for Fig 18 and 0.1 mm for Fig 19." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/172488/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Fig. 
<number box="[540,572,807,833]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
). There are 
<number box="[736,751,807,833]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="3.0">3</number>
(– 
<number box="[774,790,807,833]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="4.0">4</number>
) thick hairs on the medial surface of the hypandrium, the bilobed surstyli have numerous short, distinct hairs and the gonopods bear minute hairs (
<figureCitation box="[486,574,887,913]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 20" captionStartId="9.[264,383,1778,1802]" captionTargetBox="[397,1195,325,1770]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[389,1200,317,1787]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 20: D. meigenii male genitalia. 9: ventral view, 10: detailed ventral view with surstyli, gonopods, cerci (no hairs on cerci drawn), 11: detailed lateral view with gonopod and paramere, 12: lateral view with aedeagal apodeme, hypandrium and epandrium. Scale bar 0.4 mm for Fig 17, 20, 0.2 mm for Fig 18 and 0.1 mm for Fig 19." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/172488/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Fig. 
<number box="[542,574,887,913]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
). In lateral view the aedeagal apodeme is more straight (that of 
<taxonomicName box="[264,446,927,952]" class="Insecta" family="Diopsidae" genus="Diasemopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comoroensis">
<emphasis box="[264,446,927,952]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">D. comoroensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is curved) and also broadening towards tip. The ligament connecting to the hypandrium joins at basal 
<number box="[587,598,970,996]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[610,625,970,996]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="3.0">3</number>
rd of the aedeagal apodeme (
<figureCitation box="[972,1064,970,996]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 20" captionStartId="9.[264,383,1778,1802]" captionTargetBox="[397,1195,325,1770]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[389,1200,317,1787]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 20: D. meigenii male genitalia. 9: ventral view, 10: detailed ventral view with surstyli, gonopods, cerci (no hairs on cerci drawn), 11: detailed lateral view with gonopod and paramere, 12: lateral view with aedeagal apodeme, hypandrium and epandrium. Scale bar 0.4 mm for Fig 17, 20, 0.2 mm for Fig 18 and 0.1 mm for Fig 19." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/172488/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Fig. 
<number box="[1030,1064,970,996]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
). The epandrium and cerci have long, dispersed hairs along their surface. Hairs on the hypandrium are reaching to the lateral part and are longer than those of 
<taxonomicName box="[852,1040,1050,1075]" class="Insecta" family="Diopsidae" genus="Diasemopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comoroensis">
<emphasis box="[852,1040,1050,1075]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">D. comoroensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The distal half of the paramere is slightly narrowing towards the tip (
<figureCitation box="[820,907,1090,1116]" captionStart="FIGURES 17 – 20" captionStartId="9.[264,383,1778,1802]" captionTargetBox="[397,1195,325,1770]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[389,1200,317,1787]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 17 – 20: D. meigenii male genitalia. 9: ventral view, 10: detailed ventral view with surstyli, gonopods, cerci (no hairs on cerci drawn), 11: detailed lateral view with gonopod and paramere, 12: lateral view with aedeagal apodeme, hypandrium and epandrium. Scale bar 0.4 mm for Fig 17, 20, 0.2 mm for Fig 18 and 0.1 mm for Fig 19." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/172488/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Fig. 
<number box="[875,907,1090,1116]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[312,912,1129,1156]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="11.[264,1323,284,1156]" box="[312,912,1129,1156]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,465,1129,1155]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Distribution</emphasis>
: Widespread in Afro­tropical regions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
